and unjustly overlooked. Drawing on extensive interviews with Velasco, her family, and film industry professionals, as well as on archival research, Seraina Rohrer offers the first full account of Velasco’s life; her portrayal of La India María in vaudeville, television, and sixteen feature film comedies, including Ni de aquí, ni de allá [Neither here, nor there]; and her controversial reception in Mexico and the United States. Rohrer traces the films’ financing, production, and distribution, as well as censorship practices of the period, and compares them to other Mexploitation films produced at the same time. Adding a new chapter to the history of a much-understudied period of Mexican cinema commonly referred to as “la crisis,” this pioneering research enriches our appreciation of Mexploitation films.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aExploitation filmszMexicoxHistory and criticism. 0aExploitation films-Mexico-History and criticism. 0aLow budget filmszMexicoxHistory and criticism. 0aLow budget films-Mexico-History and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszMexico. 0aSensationalism in motion pictures. 0aVelasco, María Elena. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorszMexico. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directors-Mexico. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31344240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477313466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477313466/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK